Do you do the same anytime you ask a co-worker a question:<p>Jim: &quot;Hey Marge, do you know how to escape a flarb?&quot;<p>Marge: &quot;Yea, call FlarbLib.EscapeFlarb&quot;<p>Jim: &quot;Ok&quot;<p><pre><code>     // <summary>
     // From Marge
     // </summary>
     string escapedFlarb = FlarbLib.EscapeFlarb(unescapedFlarb);
</code></pre>
I guess I see stack overflow as just an extension of asking a co-worker. It&#x27;s just the internet lets us all be co-workers remotely.<p>Sure if it&#x27;s some details answer that says why you&#x27;re doing something a certain way (like must use 2.0 SDK because 3.0 is broken on Linux. See <a href="http://so/1234" rel="nofollow">http://so/1234</a><p>But otherwise it seems crazy to me to have it litter the code with attributions for tiny snippets of answers.
